<br>
I can understand your aggravation against Projection for not allowing you to post here. But let me give my two cents about this argument. I think that if you are here at this message board to post messages that try to agitate, incite or subvert the undertakings and endeavors of this website then the webmaster has a right to ban your name etc. However, if you are genuinely and legitimately here for the common goal of seeing nuclear propulsion become a reality, then we welcome you and look forward to your criticisms. I am fairly new to this message board so I am not aware of what has been going on between you and Projection. Perhaps he is little overzealous and too protective about his ideals, but I think the scheme of trying to come back again and again, not only immature but somewhat demoralizing and self defeating as well. What's in it you? If everyone here has their convictions about the topic matter you’re only going to make yourself less liked by the members here.  As I said before, I have not been here long enough to observe Projection’s behavior, but I don’t think we should let the issue distract us too much from the main goal/s. <br>
<br>
The stance of bring pro-nuclear for space applications is not an easy path. Although nuclear rocket technology was well on its way to being the next step in space travel in the 1960’s and even recognized as such by Wernher Von Braun and many prominent scientists, it became political correct in the early 1970’s to abandon all funding, testing and research on nuclear applications in space. And now, Stifled, I ask of you: if you know that Humanity’s future and destiny lie in colonizing our Solar System and that the vital first step of many steps must come from enhanced and improved propulsion systems, will you not join us in promoting the future of Humankind? The road that leads to nowhere in space is called chemical rockets, for we cannot send the seed of the Human species out into the cosmos in slow, variable chemical boats. Indeed, we cannot amass significant large amounts of payload in Low Earth Orbit rationally without the low fuel weight that a nuclear rocket vehicle provides. If we want to genuinely see a future of Humans in space with the support of these attempts backed up by adequate means, then the future points to nuclear power functions. <br>
